        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  To normalize xlsx-like documents (.xls, .ods) into the XLSX format via LibreOffice headless conversion, providing a uniform input format for downstream spreadsheet readers. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  Excel-like document format normalization via soffice. \par \b Input\/ \:  Files with excel-like extensions or MIME types. \par \b Output\/ \:  Converted .xlsx file path. \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_API(9): LibreOffice soffice; READS_DATA_FROM(7): <ref refid="namespacededoc_1_1extensions_1aac3b199243c8795f127aefef6c73fa04" kindref="member">dedoc.extensions.converted_extensions</ref>] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>convert() always invokes soffice with <ndash/>headless <ndash/>convert-to xlsx.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Output file path is always {dir}/{name_wo_ext}.xlsx. \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why soffice instead of openpyxl for conversion? A: soffice handles legacy binary .xls and .ods formats that openpyxl cannot read. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 — Added semantic markup and LDD logging] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CLASS 9[Converts excel-like formats to XLSX via LibreOffice] =&gt; ExcelConverter \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[ExcelConverter.convert]: User (Upload) → NormalizeToXlsx → XlsxFileReady </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
